[{"sha":"f0a5facdba442ec9095e701c571be4552b4821ec","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. This commit extracts the remaining UI logic from the local backend,
and removes access to the direct CLI output. This is replaced with an
instance of a `views.Operation` interface, which codifies the current
requirements for the local backend to interact with the user.

The exception to this at present is interactivity: approving a plan
still depends on the `UIIn` field for the backend. This is out of scope
for this commit and can be revisited separately, at which time the
`UIOut` field can also be removed.

Changes in support of this:

- Some instances of direct error output have been replaced with
  diagnostics, most notably in the emergency state backup handler. This
  requires reformatting the error messages to allow the diagnostic
  renderer to line-wrap them;
- The "in-automation" logic has moved out of the backend and into the
  view implementation;
- The plan, apply, refresh, and import commands instantiate a view and
  set it on the `backend.Operation` struct, as these are the only code
  paths which call the `local.Operation()` method that requires it;
- The show command requires the plan rendering code which is now in the
  views package, so there is a stub implementation of a `views.Show`
  interface there.

Other refactoring work in support of migrating these commands to the
common views code structure will come in follow-up PRs, at which point
we will be able to remove the UI instances from the unit tests for those
commands.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/68558ccd54e4f1eed7213af9c1b62d7c0e049fdd"},{"sha":"7f8b8a904686bb76a12d591f3b1414cfbf9693c1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27808 from hashicorp/alisdair/command-views-operation-view

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/1d2a66009335f682ccb2539360d4259ed778daee"},{"sha":"4be54532151f411bd04faf508c45bb89c4bf3841","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fallback to  manifest list when no platform match

In some cases, in fact many in the wild, an image may have the incorrect
platform on the image config.
This can lead to failures to run an image, particularly when a user
specifies a `--platform`.
Typically what we see in the wild is a manifest list with an an entry
for, as an example, linux/arm64 pointing to an image config that has
linux/amd64 on it.

This change falls back to looking up the manifest list for an image to
see if the manifest list shows the image as the correct one for that
platform.

In order to accomplish this we need to traverse the leases associated
with an image. Each image, if pulled with Docker 20.10, will have the
manifest list stored in the containerd content store with the resource
assigned to a lease keyed on the image ID.
So we look up the lease for the image, then look up the assocated
resources to find the manifest list, then check the manifest list for a
platform match, then ensure that manifest referes to our image config.

This is only used as a fallback when a user specified they want a

[{"sha":"24e7a5596b43104997090f7e3bfd4f5222667e6d","author":{"name":"Jessica Stenning","email":"c7b75079430166e4ebf34f420cb7b84fcd25e5e6@hotmail.co.uk"},"message":"Fix sentence in v0.14 upgrade guide","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/24e7a5596b43104997090f7e3bfd4f5222667e6d"},{"sha":"68558ccd54e4f1eed7213af9c1b62d7c0e049fdd","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"backend/local: Replace CLI with view instance

This commit extracts the remaining UI logic from the local backend,
and removes access to the direct CLI output. This is replaced with an
instance of a `views.Operation` interface, which codifies the current
requirements for the local backend to interact with the user.

The exception to this at present is interactivity: approving a plan
still depends on the `UIIn` field for the backend. This is out of scope
for this commit and can be revisited separately, at which time the
`UIOut` field can also be removed.

Changes in support of this:

- Some instances of direct error output have been replaced with
  diagnostics, most notably in the emergency state backup handler. This
  requires reformatting the error messages to allow the diagnostic
  renderer to line-wrap them;
- The "in-automation" logic has moved out of the backend and into the
  view implementation;
- The plan, apply, refresh, and import commands instantiate a view and
  set it on the `backend.Operation` struct, as these are the only code
  paths which call the `local.Operation()` method that requires it;
- The show command requires the plan rendering code which is now in the
  views package, so there is a stub implementation of a `views.Show`
  interface there.

Other refactoring work in support of migrating these commands to the
common views code structure will come in follow-up PRs, at which point
we will be able to remove the UI instances from the unit tests for those
commands.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/68558ccd54e4f1eed7213af9c1b62d7c0e049fdd"},{"sha":"7f8b8a904686bb76a12d591f3b1414cfbf9693c1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27808 from hashicorp/alisdair/command-views-operation-view

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/1d2a66009335f682ccb2539360d4259ed778daee"},{"sha":"4be54532151f411bd04faf508c45bb89c4bf3841","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fallback to  manifest list when no platform match

In some cases, in fact many in the wild, an image may have the incorrect
platform on the image config.
This can lead to failures to run an image, particularly when a user
specifies a `--platform`.
Typically what we see in the wild is a manifest list with an an entry
for, as an example, linux/arm64 pointing to an image config that has
linux/amd64 on it.

This change falls back to looking up the manifest list for an image to
see if the manifest list shows the image as the correct one for that
platform.

In order to accomplish this we need to traverse the leases associated
with an image. Each image, if pulled with Docker 20.10, will have the
manifest list stored in the containerd content store with the resource
assigned to a lease keyed on the image ID.
So we look up the lease for the image, then look up the assocated
resources to find the manifest list, then check the manifest list for a
platform match, then ensure that manifest referes to our image config.

This is only used as a fallback when a user specified they want a
particular platform and the image config that we have does not match
that platform.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/4be54532151f411bd04faf508c45bb89c4bf3841"},{"sha":"50f39e724707ef121a988e422eb52045d3754802","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Move cpu variant checks into platform matcher

Wrap platforms.Only and fallback to our ignore mismatches due to  empty

The previous changes removing support for using the trailing positional
argument as a working directory missed a spot in the apply/destroy
command implementation. We still support this argument for applying a
saved plan:

    terraform apply foo.tfplan

However, if you pass a positional path which doesn't "look like" a plan
(for example, the path to a configuration directory), Terraform would
silently ignore it and continue.

This commit fixes that by adding an error message if the user specifies
a path which the plan loader rejects as not "looking like" a plan. This
message includes a reference to the `-chdir` flag as a pointer about
what to do next.

We also rearrange the error message when calling `terraform destroy`
with a plan file argument, and add test coverage for the above. While
we're here, update the destroy tests to copy the fixture directory,
chdir, and defer cleanup.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bmelbourne/terraform/commits/d7613a0aac1f42f9e05e9d9c3a3d9d53b554ddfa"},{"sha":"181048b9133278640a52dd6d0b509fd875f7e764","author":{"name":"Robin Norwood","email":"10d4ff146f9492e67370a28ec1fa3795cc8904fc@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Add crosslink to new Learn tutorial","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bmelbourne/terraform/commits/181048b9133278640a52dd6d0b509fd875f7e764"},{"sha":"f279bf58c440f6f348e2d284a37c49727c743c80","author":{"name":"Robin Norwood","email":"10d4ff146f9492e67370a28ec1fa3795cc8904fc@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27689 from hashicorp/rln-data-sources-tutorial

This is the first commit for plugin protocol v6. This is currently
unused (dead) code; future commits will add the necessary conversion
packages, extend configschema, and modify the providers.Interface.

The new plugin protocol includes the following changes:

- A new field has been added to Attribute: NestedType. This will be the
  key new feature in plugin protocol v6
- Several massages were renamed for consistency with the verb-noun
  pattern seen in _most_ messages.
- The prepared_config has been removed from PrepareProviderConfig
  (renamed ValidateProviderConfig), as it has never been used.
- The provisioner service has been removed entirely. This has no impact
  on built-in provisioners. 3rd party provisioners are not supported by
  the SDK and are not included in this protocol at all.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bmelbourne/terraform/commits/f3a057eb3567eee0d51c185fc0a7922852b2e060"},{"sha":"3ad720e9dca5503ff3be9def0d0e33ab9ef7fb33","author":{"name":"Kristin Laemmert","email":"30cb4a936f196f8da41f6469d07b31397d334edc@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"configs/configschema: add new NestedType to attribute

  fully-merged version constraints for the entire module, instead of any
  constraints set in the provider configuration block itself;
- After all provider configurations are processed, iterate over the

whole-resource diagnostic, but then doesn't associate it with any

the config at all.

This commit extracts the remaining UI logic from the local backend,
and removes access to the direct CLI output. This is replaced with an
instance of a `views.Operation` interface, which codifies the current
requirements for the local backend to interact with the user.

The exception to this at present is interactivity: approving a plan
still depends on the `UIIn` field for the backend. This is out of scope
for this commit and can be revisited separately, at which time the
`UIOut` field can also be removed.

Changes in support of this:

- Some instances of direct error output have been replaced with
  diagnostics, most notably in the emergency state backup handler. This
  requires reformatting the error messages to allow the diagnostic
  renderer to line-wrap them;
- The "in-automation" logic has moved out of the backend and into the
  view implementation;
- The plan, apply, refresh, and import commands instantiate a view and
  set it on the `backend.Operation` struct, as these are the only code
  paths which call the `local.Operation()` method that requires it;
- The show command requires the plan rendering code which is now in the
  views package, so there is a stub implementation of a `views.Show`
  interface there.

Other refactoring work in support of migrating these commands to the
common views code structure will come in follow-up PRs, at which point
we will be able to remove the UI instances from the unit tests for those
commands.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/68558ccd54e4f1eed7213af9c1b62d7c0e049fdd"},{"sha":"7f8b8a904686bb76a12d591f3b1414cfbf9693c1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27808 from hashicorp/alisdair/command-views-operation-view

This commit extracts the remaining UI logic from the local backend,
and removes access to the direct CLI output. This is replaced with an
instance of a `views.Operation` interface, which codifies the current
requirements for the local backend to interact with the user.

The exception to this at present is interactivity: approving a plan
still depends on the `UIIn` field for the backend. This is out of scope
for this commit and can be revisited separately, at which time the
`UIOut` field can also be removed.

Changes in support of this:

- Some instances of direct error output have been replaced with
  diagnostics, most notably in the emergency state backup handler. This
  requires reformatting the error messages to allow the diagnostic
  renderer to line-wrap them;
- The "in-automation" logic has moved out of the backend and into the
  view implementation;
- The plan, apply, refresh, and import commands instantiate a view and
  set it on the `backend.Operation` struct, as these are the only code
  paths which call the `local.Operation()` method that requires it;
- The show command requires the plan rendering code which is now in the
  views package, so there is a stub implementation of a `views.Show`
  interface there.

Other refactoring work in support of migrating these commands to the
common views code structure will come in follow-up PRs, at which point
we will be able to remove the UI instances from the unit tests for those
commands.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/terraform/commits/68558ccd54e4f1eed7213af9c1b62d7c0e049fdd"},{"sha":"7f8b8a904686bb76a12d591f3b1414cfbf9693c1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27808 from hashicorp/alisdair/command-views-operation-view

and removes access to the direct CLI output. This is replaced with an
instance of a `views.Operation` interface, which codifies the current
requirements for the local backend to interact with the user.

The exception to this at present is interactivity: approving a plan
still depends on the `UIIn` field for the backend. This is out of scope
for this commit and can be revisited separately, at which time the
`UIOut` field can also be removed.

Changes in support of this:

- Some instances of direct error output have been replaced with
  diagnostics, most notably in the emergency state backup handler. This
  requires reformatting the error messages to allow the diagnostic
  renderer to line-wrap them;
- The "in-automation" logic has moved out of the backend and into the
  view implementation;
- The plan, apply, refresh, and import commands instantiate a view and
  set it on the `backend.Operation` struct, as these are the only code
  paths which call the `local.Operation()` method that requires it;
- The show command requires the plan rendering code which is now in the
  views package, so there is a stub implementation of a `views.Show`
  interface there.

Other refactoring work in support of migrating these commands to the
common views code structure will come in follow-up PRs, at which point
we will be able to remove the UI instances from the unit tests for those
commands.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MartiUK/terraform/commits/68558ccd54e4f1eed7213af9c1b62d7c0e049fdd"},{"sha":"7f8b8a904686bb76a12d591f3b1414cfbf9693c1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27808 from hashicorp/alisdair/command-views-operation-view

[{"sha":"5f775be482f4201c487a7a69afe90a512d9de8b9","author":{"name":"Sung Jin Hwang","email":"a940ffff6bf8d31e6d61496a80ea1172885a64d6@google.com"},"message":"Disable summary step error when summaries are disabled.

Summary write functions do not complain about steps when summary writer is not
configured, but they do complain when summary write is disabled by
`tf.summary.record_if(False)`. This change makes the error detection more
consistent, and makes the summary function not raise errors of missing step
numbers when summary is disabled.

[{"sha":"4be54532151f411bd04faf508c45bb89c4bf3841","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fallback to  manifest list when no platform match

In some cases, in fact many in the wild, an image may have the incorrect
platform on the image config.
This can lead to failures to run an image, particularly when a user
specifies a `--platform`.
Typically what we see in the wild is a manifest list with an an entry
for, as an example, linux/arm64 pointing to an image config that has
linux/amd64 on it.

This change falls back to looking up the manifest list for an image to
see if the manifest list shows the image as the correct one for that
platform.

In order to accomplish this we need to traverse the leases associated
with an image. Each image, if pulled with Docker 20.10, will have the
manifest list stored in the containerd content store with the resource
assigned to a lease keyed on the image ID.
So we look up the lease for the image, then look up the assocated
resources to find the manifest list, then check the manifest list for a
platform match, then ensure that manifest referes to our image config.

This is only used as a fallback when a user specified they want a
particular platform and the image config that we have does not match
that platform.

So we look up the lease for the image, then look up the assocated
resources to find the manifest list, then check the manifest list for a
platform match, then ensure that manifest referes to our image config.

This is only used as a fallback when a user specified they want a
particular platform and the image config that we have does not match
that platform.

[{"sha":"4be54532151f411bd04faf508c45bb89c4bf3841","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fallback to  manifest list when no platform match

In some cases, in fact many in the wild, an image may have the incorrect
platform on the image config.
This can lead to failures to run an image, particularly when a user
specifies a `--platform`.
Typically what we see in the wild is a manifest list with an an entry
for, as an example, linux/arm64 pointing to an image config that has
linux/amd64 on it.

This change falls back to looking up the manifest list for an image to
see if the manifest list shows the image as the correct one for that
platform.

In order to accomplish this we need to traverse the leases associated
with an image. Each image, if pulled with Docker 20.10, will have the
manifest list stored in the containerd content store with the resource
assigned to a lease keyed on the image ID.
So we look up the lease for the image, then look up the assocated
resources to find the manifest list, then check the manifest list for a
platform match, then ensure that manifest referes to our image config.

This is only used as a fallback when a user specified they want a
particular platform and the image config that we have does not match
that platform.

[{"sha":"4be54532151f411bd04faf508c45bb89c4bf3841","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fallback to  manifest list when no platform match

In some cases, in fact many in the wild, an image may have the incorrect
platform on the image config.
This can lead to failures to run an image, particularly when a user
specifies a `--platform`.
Typically what we see in the wild is a manifest list with an an entry
for, as an example, linux/arm64 pointing to an image config that has
linux/amd64 on it.

This change falls back to looking up the manifest list for an image to
see if the manifest list shows the image as the correct one for that
platform.

In order to accomplish this we need to traverse the leases associated
with an image. Each image, if pulled with Docker 20.10, will have the
manifest list stored in the containerd content store with the resource
assigned to a lease keyed on the image ID.
So we look up the lease for the image, then look up the assocated
resources to find the manifest list, then check the manifest list for a
platform match, then ensure that manifest referes to our image config.

This is only used as a fallback when a user specified they want a
particular platform and the image config that we have does not match
that platform.
